Conclusion: The following pairwise correlations are statistically significantly at the 5% level: Resp 1 vs. Resp 2 (categorisation factor(s) level A 2), Resp 3 vs. Resp 4 (categorisation factor(s) level A 2), Resp 1 vs. Resp 3 (categorisation factor(s) level B 1), Resp 3 vs. Resp 4 (categorisation factor(s) level C 1), Resp 3 vs. Resp 4 (categorisation factor(s) level C 2), Resp 1 vs. Resp 2 (categorisation factor(s) level D 1), Resp 3 vs. Resp 4 (categorisation factor(s) level D 1), Resp 3 vs. Resp 4 (categorisation factor(s) level D 2).

Note that there is only one or two pairs of responses available for one or more of the level(s) of the categorisation factor(s) and hence no correlation analysis can be performed for the level(s) of the categorisation factor(s).

Analysis description

This test is a rank-based measure of association and can be used when the data are not necessarily from a bivariate normal distribution, see Hollander and Wolfe (1973). The p-values are computed using algorithm AS 89, see Best and Roberts (1975).

For more information on the theoretical approaches that are implemented within this module, see Bate and Clark (2014).
